TY  - THES
AU  - Zhang, Huan
AB  - Understanding and accurately estimating rare events in high-dimensional systems is a central challenge in applied mathematics, physics, and computational science. This dissertation develops new methodologies that integrate machine learning with domain-specific knowledge to improve tail accuracy in probabilistic modeling and the study of extreme events.The thesis begins by addressing tail behavior in quantum ground state estimation, introducing techniques to mitigate spurious modes and improve wavefunction accuracy within the Variational Monte Carlo framework. Subsequent work contributes theoretical insights into the stability and error analysis of time-dependent parametric solvers for partial differential equations, unifying optimize-then-discretize and discretize-then-optimize training schemes. The study then shifts to the climate sciences, where it develops a transfer learning framework combining Convolutional Neural Networks and Explainable AI to forecast the persistence of Atlantic blocking events from limited observational data. Finally, a novel low-variance algorithm is proposed for estimating large deviation rate functions in high-dimensional stochastic systems by learning transport terms that evolve particle ensembles along rare-event trajectories. Collectively, these contributions demonstrate how machine learning techniques—when informed by physical structure and mathematical principles—can significantly enhance our understanding and predictive capabilities for tail phenomena across scientific disciplines.
TI  - Learning the Tails of Distributions and Processes in Physics
LA  - eng
PY  - 2025
PB  - ProQuest Dissertations & Theses
